at|

Now, point count:
I think that a reasonable approach to Michaels is to start off playing them to show some point count range
Like 6-12, and with more power, the overcaller plans to bid both of her suits.

This way, if opener on your right bids 1@H and you have  @sKQJxx  @hKx  @dx  @cAQJ10x, 
all you really need for a play at 4@S is for advancer to have 3 spades to the Ace 
(and with @SAxx and the @CK, 4@S is almost 100% cold)

So instead of a Michaels bid, you would overcall 1@H with 1@S and plan to bid clubs later, 
unless pard raises spades aggressively, in which case, you'd just blast off!

sebstar: I presume michaels is forcing bid (p cannot pass) and alertable?
mitche: Yes, and no.  All cue bids are "self-alerting", and pard is expected to pick one of your suits. 
But since people will occasionally open 1@C on 3 of them, advancer might pass 2@C 
with  @sxx  @hxx  @dxx  @cKQ10xxxx or the like.
